default&#xa0;
default5.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultCar 
defaultclubs can provide a cost effective and financially sustainable alternative to dependency on taxis, DRT services and private car ownership and use in isolated communities.
default5.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhere it is not possible or feasible to provide any other public transport service, w
defaulte think car clubs provide an option not to own a car in areas where cars are sometimes the only way to undertake some activities.
default5.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultCommunities of a size sufficient to support a financially sustainable car club should not have to rely on taxi and DRT service
defaults. Through the Transport Scotland 
defaultDeveloping Car Clubs in Scotland 
defaultprogramme, Carplus has provided technical and financial assistance to support a number of community-run car clubs in isolated rural communities. For example the DCCS programme funded the de
defaultvelopment of a community-run car club in Fintry, Stirlingshire, a community located 17 miles from Stirling and 18 miles from Glasgow. This car club provides two pay-as-you-drive cars which can be booked on-line or over the phone and which provide a conveni
defaultent and cost effective alternative to private car ownership and use. As one local resident puts it: 
default“With no Public transport in Fintry, residents have had a high dependency on cars. We kept one car, sold our second and both my husband and I joined the ca
defaultr club. This has been ideal for our needs. We’ve saved considerable sums on the costs of maintaining and insuring another vehicle .The car club offers us a choice of car size to suit need and preference. Being car club members 
defaultdiscourages lazy unnecessary 
defaultcar use and therefore benefits users and the environment”.
default Kayt Howell, car club member FEET car club, Fintry, Stirlingshire.
default5.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHere are some more examples of the benefits of developing car clubs in small towns and rural communities in member’s own words:
default“I
default am the only driver in my family and there are two members who require care support daily. They live in opposite directions from my home 18 and 22 miles apart, so having access to a motor vehicle is essential. As a pensioner I have to watch the cost of pro
defaultviding this support and the car club car gave me the means to provide the service. The peace of mind knowing that in an emergency I can still be mobile is difficult to put into words.” 
defaultStuart MacVicar, car club member LEAP Car Club, Lochwinnoch, Renfrewshi
defaultre.
default"Westwheels cars have enabled me to take up to four children away on school trips which I would be struggling to achieve in this area where there's limited public transport. Because of WestWheels, we do not need to keep a car on the mainland which mean
defaults our costs are reduced. I think the Car Club is a good asset to our area.”
default Sue Holland, island resident and WestWheels car club member, Mallaig the Highlands.
